    {
        "content": "<p>rfl doesn't simplify numeric expressions, but it unfolds definitions to try and get the values to match. For example, if you have <code>2 + 2 = 4</code>, then it will unfold it as <code>2 + 2 = 2 + (1 + 1) = (2 + 1) + 1 = (2 + (0 + 1)) + 1 = ((2 + 0) + 1) + 1 = (2 + 1) + 1 = 3  + 1 = 4</code> (this is not 100% true for integers, as the kernel has special support for them to make it more efficient, but that's the idea).<br>\nAlso note that the tactic <code>rfl</code> only tries to apply <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=rfl#doc\">docs#rfl</a>, which means it says \"I have a proof that <code>2 + 2 = 4</code> - by reflexivity <code>2 + 2 = 2 + 2</code>, and that's what we need\", and then type checking verifies that <code>2 + 2 = 4</code> and <code>2 + 2 = 2 + 2</code> are definitionally equal (defeq), so it tries to unify <code>4</code> with <code>2 + 2</code></p>",
        "id": 472660083,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1727259329
    },
